\normalsize
\textsc{Abstract:}

\LARGE
How CAN a ``function'' from $\mathbb{R}$ to $\mathbb{R}$ have the
property that it is zero everywhere except at $x = 0$, but have
integral 1? Why is such a function useful?  How can such a
``function'' be put in a mathematically rigorous context? How is
it a building block for solving many differential equations? 
\\

